 <p><hr><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#FFFF00" vlink="#00FF00" alink="#00FF00"><div align="center"><center><table border="3" cellspacing="0" bordercolor="#008080" bordercolordark="#000000" bordercolorlight="#008080"><tr><td valign="top" width="100%" background="http://www.thedruidsgrove.org/images/sobe/back.gif"><p align="center"><font color="#80FF00" size="4" face="Trebuchet MS"><strong>Sobe Silvertree</strong></font><font color="#FFFF80" face="Trebuchet MS"><br></font><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">"</font><a href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/members.cgi?page=details&character=Sobe" target="new"><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">The Wanderer</font></a><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">" and "</font><a href="http://www.geocities.com/kibadachi_uk/epiclink.htm" target="new"><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">1st Tunarian Protector</font></a><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">"<br>Elder Hierophant of </font><a href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/" target="new"><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">Guild Afterlife</font></a><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS"><br>Administrator of </font><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS"> </font><a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove" target="new"><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS">The Druids Grove</font></a><font color="#FFFF80" size="2" face="Trebuchet MS"></font></p></td></tr></table></center></div></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uxerius1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xerius1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 7:57:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=432>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To Zan</span><hr size=1> It appears one of the primary problems here is the perception of the druid's place in high level raids.<br>
<br>
The initial petition complains that druids are no longer viable healers in high level situations, while Clerics and Shamen remain capable of healing under those circumstances (among other things, but that one issue seems to be what ninety percent of the discussion is revolving around).<br>
<br>
Perhaps the problem is not in the druid, but in the perception of his place in the raid.<br>
<br>
There are only three classes in the game who never change their focus throughout their entire game life.  Warriors start the game hitting small things with large weapons, and never stop until level 60, although the things they hit get meaner and the large weapons get larger.  Clerics begin the game healing the wounds caused by the random creatures that one sees throughout Norrath and Luclin, and by the end of their levels, they are still healing, although they are considerably better at it.  Wizards start out with the ability to do damage to anything that looks like it might be dangerous, and although they do broaden their focus a bit over time, by 60 they still are essentially large artillary pieces, doing extreme amounts of damage until they are out of mana, then essentially helpless, since their largest function has been exhausted.<br>
<br>
And then we come to every other class in the game (except perhaps the Beastlords, since the discussion is still out as to what the extent of their function is at all levels).  Necromancers start the game as Lifetappers, their vaunted pets of only minimal use until level 4 (or 8 depending on which Necro you talk to).  They eventually broaden their horizons to become a major pet class, a class that can Heal, use Dots, limited DD (very limited), and develop into a more group friendly class as time goes on, until their original purpose has very little resemblance to final product.  Rogues and Monks start their careers as second class Warriors, developing eventually into the highest damage output 'tank' class in the game, within rigid parameters (they cannot take damage and require a Taunting class to take damage for them).  The Shamen start the game as much tanks as casters, due to the armour they can wear, developing first into a Healer and DOT class, losing Healing power in relation to the dedicated Healing class of the Cleric, but soon gaining a pet, and never losing the title of the Buffing Class of Everquest.  And so we continue through every class in the game.<br>
<br>
What then of the druids?  If you hold that they are not a viable healing class after 55, is it possible that they are not intended to be?  Many have disagreed, citing that the druids are still a very capable healing class clear up to 60 in all situations, while others (one can discount Aidon, since he is so busy running into trees that it has not occurred to him yet that there might be a forest) believe that is not true.  Could this be because druids are intended to have another function after 55 that is not so based on their ability (or lack of ability) to heal?  Or perhaps this new role is not fully workable, and some provision should be made to enhance it after 55, perhaps at the cost of any Healing spells after that level (balance must be maintained).<br>
<br>
I do realize that the primary argument is that balance is not currently maintained, although the 'gimme list' is somewhat laughable, containing as it does enhanced versions of existing specialist spells in almost every area of the game (missing only demands for Lures, Resses and Complete Heal, and some of the advocates of the gimme list have demanded those too).<br>
<br>
There are probably three primary alternatives.<br>
<br>
First, the list can be modified back to a realistic point.  A self only version of Protection of the Grove is quite viable and very reasonable, since the Clerics do indeed have a precedent with their self only Buff line.  Stacking issues can likewise be examined, perhaps finding a way to stack symbols, high level Cleric buffs or general high level buffs with the high level druid buffs (or at least a compromise, as has been made with other stacking issues, where some aspects stack and others are over written).  Beyond that, Cold and Fire based versions of Winged Death, with identical mana cost and damage?  A cold based equivalent to Ro's Smouldering Disjunction?  I would hesitate to add either of those, although they would certainly be worth examining for suitability and balance.<br>
<br>
A second possibility would involve a major reworking of the class, but would be viable.  Remove the 10 percent penalty for Healing, and even add five percent to that, at the cost of all Snare spells.  Give Complete Heal to the druid class, at the cost of all DD and DOT spells.  Give better hit point and AC buffs, at the cost of Port and movement spells, then to balance it, add lower grade DD spells, enhanced against the undead.  Many posts in this discussion have agreed that makes a balanced class, and it would certainly give the healing abilities the original post desired.<br>
<br>
A third possibility involves looking at the class as a whole, instead of only a portion of it.  It takes as long to get from 50 to 60 as it does from 1 to 50, so we can consider this petition to be involving only a quarter of the life of the character (assuming 55 to 60 being half of the road from 50 to 60, which it is not, but we need some sort of rough benchmark).  The druid class is held to be very powerful from 1 to 55, not only in its ability to solo (the argument of many here), but also in its ability to do virtually everything, even if it is not done as well as the class with a distinctive in the ability.  Should a limitation on 55 to 60 be considered a reasonable price to pay for excess power from 1 to 55? (whether there is indeed excess power at those levels is a point for another post, since the originators of this petition have insisted those levels not be considered)<br>
<br>
The bottom line though, is that in spite of the insistance that the levels from 1 to 55 not be considered for the purpose of this discussion, the gimme list attempts to define the role of the druid from 55 to 60 as being the same role the druid has played from 1 to 55, and I would not be so fast to assume that, since so few other classes keep the same role throughout their entire life.<br>
<br>
And the standard replies to the trolls who attempt to reply to any argument they do not agree with.  I do play in the high level game as both caster and tank, but do not play a druid myself.  I group with druids, my guild employs them in the high level game, I have grouped with them both before and after 55.  I have found many druids that I regularly hunt with have little problem finding groups, because from 1 to 55 they created reputations for themselves as good group members, and I have seen druids haunting zone borders shouting for groups who do not get them, because they soloed from 1 to 55, and nobody in the high end game has every heard of them.<br>
